== Name ==
At the time Joseph Smith dictated the Book of Mormon, Alma was known only as a woman's name. Recent historical research indicates it may have been a masculine name among Jewish people around 600 B.C., which is the time Lehi left Jerusalem according to the Book of Mormon.<ref name=":0">{{cite web|author=Paul Y. Hoskisson |url=http://maxwellinstitute.byu.edu/publications/jbms/?vol=7&num=1&id=173 |title=What's in a Name? Alma as a Hebrew Name - Paul Y. Hoskisson - Journal of Book of Mormon Studies - Volume 7 - Issue 1 |publisher=Maxwellinstitute.byu.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-07-24}}</ref>

A potential Hebrew meaning of the name may be "lad of God" and “He [God] is bound.” Alma may possibly be traced to the Arabic root ''‘alama/’ ‘alima,'' suggesting “knowing, erudite; distinguished; chief, chieftain."<ref name=":0" />

